<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="feature-prioritization-moscow">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-manager</domain>
    <summary>MoSCoW categorizes requirements into Must/Should/Could/Won't for a fixed-timebox release. Core rule: Must passes the fail-test and Must+Should must not exceed 80% of capacity.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>prioritization</tag>
      <tag>moscow</tag>
      <tag>scoping</tag>
      <tag>requirements</tag>
      <tag>timebox</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Feature Prioritization (MoSCoW)</title>
    <summary>MoSCoW categorizes requirements into Must Have, Should Have, Could Have, and Won't Have buckets for a fixed-timebox release. The core rule: every Must Have must pass the fail-test — "if we don't have this, does the product work?" — and Must + Should must not exceed 80% of capacity.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Without a shared priority vocabulary, every requirement becomes "high priority" and scope creep is uncontrollable. MoSCoW forces explicit trade-off decisions and, critically, requires documenting exclusions (Won't Have), which prevents scope re-entry mid-sprint.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Fixed-timebox release (sprint, milestone, MVP, contractual deadline) where capacity is the constraint</item>
        <item>Stakeholder workshop where the goal is shared vocabulary, not numerical optimization</item>
        <item>Scoping a vendor or contractor engagement: M/S/C/W maps cleanly to contract obligations</item>
        <item>Compliance and legal-driven work where "Must" carries a non-negotiable definition</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Cross-feature ROI comparison — MoSCoW does not encode effort or impact magnitude; use RICE</item>
        <item>Long-horizon roadmaps (greater than 1 quarter) — categories drift; rerun MoSCoW per release</item>
        <item>Many candidates (greater than 30 items) — categories collapse into "Must" by stakeholder pressure; use a numeric framework</item>
        <item>Strategic bets — MoSCoW cannot capture "this is a moat play, not viability"</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="category-definitions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Must Have: items that, if absent, cause the product to fail completely. Apply the fail-test verbatim — "if we don't have this, does the product work?" A "yes" means it is not Must.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a binary test, teams default to calling everything Must. The fail-test forces explicit articulation of the viability condition per item.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Should Have: important but not critical. A reasonable workaround exists. Users can accomplish their goals without it, but the experience degrades noticeably.</statement>
        <rationale>The workaround test distinguishes Should from Must. If the answer is "users can still proceed," it is Should.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Could Have: nice-to-have enhancements with low cost. First category to cut when Must+Should exceed capacity. Absence does not affect core functionality.</statement>
        <rationale>Explicit "first to cut" designation protects Must and Should from false trade-offs when capacity is tight.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Won't Have: explicitly excluded from this release. Document every Won't item with a one-line reason and optionally a future-release target.</statement>
        <rationale>Won't Have is the framework's primary scope defense. Undocumented exclusions re-enter as scope creep. The discomfort of writing Won't is the value of the exercise.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="capacity-allocation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Must Have must target 60% of capacity. Must + Should must not exceed 80%. The remaining 20% absorbs Could items or overflow.</statement>
        <rationale>Empirical heuristic from DSDM. If Must alone exceeds 60%, the release is over-scoped before a single Should item is considered.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always require a capacity number before running MoSCoW. Without a timebox (eng-weeks, person-days, or sprint budget), categories are meaningless — you are producing a wish list, not a prioritization.</statement>
        <rationale>MoSCoW categories are release-scoped, not absolute. The same feature can be Must in one release and Won't in the next depending on capacity and goal.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="must-inflation-prevention">
      <rule>
        <statement>Force at least one item into Won't Have per session. If every item passes the fail-test, the fail-test is being applied too loosely — reapply with a contrarian perspective.</statement>
        <rationale>Must inflation is the universal failure mode. A contrarian re-application ("a competitor ships without this and wins — still Must?") surfaces weak Musts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Invoice app MVP: "User authentication" passes fail-test — the product cannot work at all without identity. Must Have.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>"Password reset" is often called Must, but users can use support as a workaround. Should Have is correct unless compliance requires it.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="process-steps">
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 1 — List all requirements from stakeholder requests, user research, technical needs, and competitive analysis. Do not pre-filter.</statement>
        <rationale>Pre-filtering before categorization embeds hidden prioritization. The full list enables transparent trade-offs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 2 — Define the timebox explicitly: time horizon ("this sprint", "this quarter"), team capacity in person-days, and any budget constraints. Announce the number before categorization begins.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a published capacity number, participants anchor categories to desires rather than constraints.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 3 — Initial categorization: for each item, apply the four questions in order: (1) fails without it? → Must; (2) painful but workable without? → Should; (3) nice but not needed? → Could; (4) out of scope? → Won't.</statement>
        <rationale>Ordered questions prevent skipping directly to Could or Won't for items that should be Must.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 4 — Validate effort allocation. Sum effort per category. If Must + Should exceeds 80% of capacity, move Should items to Could, Could to Won't. Never move Must to Should.</statement>
        <rationale>The allocation check is the only mechanism that enforces scope discipline after categorization. Skipping it produces a MoSCoW list that still overflows capacity.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 5 — Stakeholder alignment: share categorization, surface disagreements, document decisions and rationale. Every Must item needs explicit stakeholder sign-off.</statement>
        <rationale>Unresolved categorization disagreements resurface as mid-sprint scope changes. Documenting decisions creates the accountability record.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 6 — Lock and track. Lock Must and Won't after sign-off — changes require escalation. Should and Could remain editable. Re-run MoSCoW per release, not per quarter.</statement>
        <rationale>Locking Must prevents "just one more Must" additions. Locking Won't prevents scope creep from excluded items being re-introduced without a full re-prioritization.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/moscow-matrix.md">MoSCoW matrix template for documenting categories with effort tracking</reference>
      <reference path="templates/moscow-capacity-validator.sh">Bash capacity validator to check Must+Should proportion</reference>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Must inflation: 60-80% of items end up categorized as Must Have.</description>
        <reason>The fail-test is applied loosely. Teams interpret "important" as "must." Without a contrarian pass, no item survives downgrade to Should.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No Won't Have category. Teams skip documenting exclusions because it is uncomfortable.</description>
        <reason>Won't Have is the primary mechanism for preventing scope creep. An empty Won't list means every excluded item is implicitly negotiable, re-entering as "just one more thing."</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No timebox declared. MoSCoW session runs without a stated capacity number.</description>
        <reason>Without capacity as a constraint, categories reflect desires rather than trade-offs. The 60/20/20 allocation cannot be validated, so the output is a wishlist, not a scoped plan.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Treating the 60/20/20 allocation as a law rather than a heuristic, and using it to mechanically assign exact effort budgets.</description>
        <reason>The allocation is a directional check. Forcing exactly 60% Must effort produces false precision. The check is: "are Must+Should within 80%?" not "is Must exactly 60%?"</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Changing Must Have items mid-sprint without escalation. PMs add scope by re-categorizing Could items as Must.</description>
        <reason>Must changes after lockdown destroy the entire value of the exercise. Every Must change must require explicit stakeholder escalation and re-validation of capacity allocation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using MoSCoW for long-horizon roadmaps (more than one quarter).</description>
        <reason>MoSCoW categories are release-scoped. Over a quarter, business context shifts enough that Must items become irrelevant and Won't items become Must. Rerun per release, not per quarter.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A scoping agent ingests the feature list plus a stated capacity (eng-weeks) and the release goal, and returns an initial M/S/C/W classification with a one-line "fail-test" per Must Have ("does product fail completely without this?"). A capacity agent sums the effort and warns if Must+Should is greater than 80% of capacity. A challenger agent attacks every Must by re-asking the fail-test from a contrarian persona ("a competitor ships without this and wins — still Must?"). Human approves; agent locks Must and Won't, leaves Should/Could editable.</p>
      <section name="recommended-subagents">
        <list>
          <item>faion-mvp-scope-analyzer-agent — initial classification, named in the README.</item>
          <item>A "must-challenger" agent — single job: re-ask the fail-test, force downgrades.</item>
          <item>A capacity-sentinel agent — runs on every backlog change, alerts when Must greater than 60%.</item>
          <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — picks up Must items first as SDD tasks.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <prompt purpose="scoping-agent"><![CDATA[Release: <name>, capacity: <X eng-weeks>, goal: <one-line>.
Candidates: <list with effort estimate per item>.
Classify each as Must / Should / Could / Won't.
For each Must include a one-line fail-test: "without this, the product fails because ___".
For each Won't include a one-line "explicitly excluded because ___".
Flag if Must+Should sum exceeds 80% of capacity.]]></prompt>
      <prompt purpose="must-challenger"><![CDATA[You are the must-challenger. For each item below currently classified Must,
state the strongest case for downgrading to Should. If you cannot construct
a credible case, leave it as Must. Output a diff, not a rewrite.]]></prompt>
    </section>
    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>gh issue list --label moscow:must — Filter GitHub issues by MoSCoW label. https://cli.github.com/manual/gh_issue_list</item>
        <item>linear-cli / Linear GraphQL — Linear has a priority field; map MoSCoW to it via API. https://developers.linear.app</item>
        <item>jq + project export — Sum effort per category to validate proportions. https://stedolan.github.io/jq/</item>
        <item>mermaid-cli — Render quadrant chart of MoSCoW classification. https://github.com/mermaid-js/mermaid-cli</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="services">
      <list>
        <item>Linear (SaaS, Yes GraphQL) — Map MoSCoW to label or custom field; agents update via API.</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects (SaaS, Yes REST/GraphQL) — Free; use labels moscow:must|should|could|wont.</item>
        <item>Notion (SaaS, Yes REST API) — DIY board with Category select column; cheap.</item>
        <item>Airfocus (SaaS, Yes API) — Native MoSCoW board view.</item>
        <item>Trello + Butler (SaaS, Limited) — List-per-category; automation moves cards by rule.</item>
        <item>OpenProject (OSS, Yes) — Custom-field MoSCoW; self-hostable.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Always require a capacity number first. MoSCoW without a timebox is feature wishlisting.</item>
        <item>Force at least 1 item into Won't Have per session — the discomfort is the value.</item>
        <item>Apply the fail-test verbatim for every Must: "If we don't have this, does the product work?" If the answer is "it works worse," the item is Should, not Must.</item>
        <item>Lock Must + Won't after stakeholder sign-off. Should/Could remain editable; Must changes require explicit escalation.</item>
        <item>Re-run MoSCoW per release, not per quarter. Categories are release-scoped, not strategic.</item>
        <item>Pair MoSCoW with a numeric framework (RICE) for the Should/Could tier — MoSCoW says "yes-if-time," RICE says "in what order."</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents over-classify as Must by default — being "comprehensive" reads as safer than being "ruthless." Add an explicit instruction: "default category is Could; promote with evidence."</item>
        <item>LLMs forget the capacity number mid-session and produce 200% allocations. Pin capacity in every system message.</item>
        <item>The Won't list is the one most often omitted; make it a required output field, not optional.</item>
        <item>Model produces vague Musts ("good UX", "fast performance"); enforce a fail-test sentence per Must.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint: every Must that exceeds 40% of capacity individually requires a co-sign — this is the most common scope-explosion vector.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint: Won't list before publication — agents frequently slip a real "Must" into Won't because it looks expensive.</item>
        <item>Don't let the agent silently reclassify items between sessions; it loses commitment context. Force a diff with rationale per change.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/moscow-matrix.md" purpose="Prioritization matrix with effort tracking and summary table"/>
      <template path="templates/moscow-capacity-validator.sh" purpose="Bash script to validate Must+Should is less than or equal to 80% of capacity from CSV"/>
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.agilebusiness.org/dsdm-project-framework/moscow-prioririsation.html"/>
      <link href="https://www.atlassian.com/agile/product-management/moscow-method"/>
      <link href="https://www.romanpichler.com/blog/20-product-prioritization-techniques/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
